LangGraph is an open-source framework developed by LangChain for building stateful, multi-agent AI applications that integrate large language models (LLMs). It lets you define, coordinate, and execute multiple LLM agents or chains as nodes in a graph, managing the flow of data and the sequence of operations. Here are some core aspects of LangGraph:

### Key Features

- **Graph-Based Architecture**: In LangGraph, applications are structured as directed graphs. Each node represents an LLM agent or computational step (such as data processing or tool-calling), and edges dictate the flow and order of operations. This allows clear and flexible control over complex workflows ([GeeksforGeeks](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/what-is-langgraph/), [DataCamp](https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/langgraph-tutorial)).
- **Stateful Execution**: LangGraph automatically manages the state, carrying information between nodes, updating it as agents perform tasks. This persistence enables multi-turn, context-aware interactions, robust to errors and interruptions ([Medium](https://medium.com/@cplog/introduction-to-langgraph-a-beginners-guide-14f9be027141)).
- **Cyclical Flows and Conditional Branches**: It enables cycles (loops) and branching logic, necessary for iterative or decision-driven workflows (e.g., retrying steps, handling exceptions, or making choices based on intermediate results) ([GeeksforGeeks](https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/machine-learning/what-is-langgraph/), [DataCamp](https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/langgraph-tutorial)).
- **Multi-Agent Systems**: LangGraph is useful for orchestrating several agents that need to interact, pass data, and coordinate actions.
- **Integration with LangChain**: While part of the LangChain ecosystem, LangGraph adds more explicit graph-based coordination; it can be used both with and without other LangChain components ([DataCamp](https://www.datacamp.com/tutorial/langgraph-tutorial), [Hugging Face](https://huggingface.co/learn/agents-course/en/unit2/langgraph/when_to_use_langgraph)).

### Use Cases

- Developing advanced chatbots with complex logic and context maintenance.
- Coordinating autonomous decision-making agents.
- Building multi-step reasoning systems.
- Workflow and process automation.
- Integrating deterministic logic with AI-powered steps (e.g., document processing, recommendation systems).

### When to Use

LangGraph shines in applications where:
- Control over the sequence of actions and detailed states is needed.
- Multi-step or conditional processes (branching, loops, retries, human-in-the-loop) are required.
- Inter-agent communication and complex orchestration are essential ([Hugging Face](https://huggingface.co/learn/agents-course/en/unit2/langgraph/when_to_use_langgraph)).

